      <div class="prose">

        <p>Labor is typically 30–50% of a construction project's cost. If you don't know your actual labor hours per job, you can't know your real margin — and you can't improve your estimating. Effective time tracking in construction needs to work for people on job sites, not just in offices.</p>

        <h2>What good construction time tracking requires</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Mobile clock-in/out:</strong> Workers must be able to log time from their phone on the job site</li>
          <li><strong>GPS verification:</strong> Confirm workers are actually at the job when they clock in</li>
          <li><strong>Job and cost code assignment:</strong> Time must be attributed to specific projects and categories (framing, electrical rough-in, etc.) for job costing to work</li>
          <li><strong>Supervisor approval:</strong> Time cards should route to a supervisor for review before payroll export</li>
          <li><strong>Payroll integration:</strong> Approved hours should flow to QuickBooks Payroll, Gusto, or similar — not require manual re-entry</li>
          <li><strong>Overtime tracking:</strong> Automatic tracking of overtime thresholds for payroll compliance</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Top platforms for construction time tracking</h2>

        <h3>Buildertrend — Best integrated time tracking for residential GCs</h3>
        <p>Buildertrend's time clock module lets field workers clock in/out with GPS verification through the mobile app. Hours are assigned to specific projects and tasks, which feeds directly into job costing. Supervisors review and approve time cards, and approved hours can export to payroll platforms.</p>

        <p>The key advantage: time tracked in Buildertrend feeds the same job costing system as your estimates and purchase orders. You can see labor cost vs. budget in real time, not weeks later after payroll closes.</p>

        <div class="cta-box">
